<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Stage 1)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The explosive has just hit the ground. <br>
<br>
           CONE SHAPED EXPLOSIVE: If it is a cone shaped device, there should be a short (2-3 ft.) opening of dirt spreading in a circle around where the bomb lands. There should be a spherical imprint based on the shape of the warhead, so if the warhead lands at a 45 degree angle, then the imprint and primary debris wall will be larger and taller/deeper on the open end of the angle, while the closed end would be completely flat<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Stage 2)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The explosive has just gone off (within a second of landing) The impact wall/primary debris wall will become 2-3 times as far away from the explosive and much taller. The edges of the wall usually begin to shape the wall into a backwards &quot;C&quot;, unless the explosion is instantaneous. A secondary debris wall will form around where the main explosion will take place, and the spherical imprint is slightly deeper within this wall. (The explosive should now be a white flare that fits slighty smaller than the inner spherical imprint)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Stage 3)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 2-4 seconds from explosion. The primary debris wall has powdered out fro mthe opposing movement (the wall is being pushed by the explosion, but denied by the obstacles or directional forces aiming towards the explosion). Also, any obstacles within 20 feet from the primary debris wall will be pushed back or shattered (depending on how close) by a preceding wave of energy from the explosion. The secondary debris wall has grown much taller (maybe 20 feet, depending on the power of the explosive element), but may have expanded no more than a few feet (again depending on the explosive element). The inner spherical imprint has grown half as deep as the secondaary debris wall (this means the explosive flare should be slightly taller than the secondary wall, and that the next stage will be the destructive force)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Stage 4)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The explosion has spread for 5-10 seconds. The primary explosive wall is much shorter, but has caused some damage (although minimal) to at least half a mile in the direction of the explosion. The secondary wall has started to form in a semisphere around the explosion, with the smoky wave folding into a funnel at the very top. Only a bright white ball and a slightly darker white imprint of the secondary wave has formed. We shall now call the secondary debris wall the destructive force.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Stage 5)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The explosion has spread for 10+ seconds. The the peak of the explosion has occured, and the destructive force has spread twice as far as the primary debris wall had, 2-3 times as fast. All obstacles have been disintegrated within the force's path. as teh destructive force pushes outward, smoke and dirt is being pushed back towards the explosion, being thrown over the inner spherical imprint, and hitting the other particles in the center, while the smoke pushes them up into the air, resembling a mushroom without a headpiece.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Stage 6)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The destructive force has faded out for up to 5 miles from the explosive. A shockwave (a wave of concentrated heat and radiation that is in the same shape of the destructive force) should be up to 10 miles from the explosion, and a final radiation wave (similar to the shockwave, but less dramatic) should be up to 20 miles from the explosion. The explosive is now a mushroom cloud, and the explosion should make the cloud bright white to orange to brown as it dies out.<br>
<br>
